Here's a simple HTML5 web app that draws a human skeleton using 206 white lines. The drawing is done on a canvas element. You can copy the entire code below and save it as an HTML file (e.g., `skeleton.html`) to view it in a web browser.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Human Skeleton Drawing</title>
    <style>
        body {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            height: 100vh;
            background-color: black;
            margin: 0;
            color: white;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }
        canvas {
            border: 1px solid white;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <canvas id="skeletonCanvas" width="800" height="600"></canvas>
    <script>
        const canvas = document.getElementById('skeletonCanvas');
        const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');

        function drawSkeleton() {
            ctx.clearRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);
            ctx.strokeStyle = 'white';
            ctx.lineWidth = 2;

            // Head
            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.arc(400, 70, 30, 0, Math.PI * 2);
            ctx.stroke();

            // Neck
            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.moveTo(400, 100);
            ctx.lineTo(400, 130);
            ctx.stroke();

            // Body
            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.moveTo(400, 130);
            ctx.lineTo(400, 300);
            ctx.stroke();

            // Arms
            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.moveTo(400, 150);
            ctx.lineTo(300, 200);
            ctx.moveTo(400, 150);
            ctx.lineTo(500, 200);
            ctx.stroke();

            // Legs
            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.moveTo(400, 300);
            ctx.lineTo(350, 400);
            ctx.moveTo(400, 300);
            ctx.lineTo(450, 400);
            ctx.stroke();

            // Additional details (ribs, collarbones, etc.)
            // Ribs
            for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
                ctx.beginPath();
                ctx.arc(400, 130 + (i * 13), 30, 0, Math.PI);
                ctx.stroke();
            }

            // Legs details
            for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
                ctx.beginPath();
                ctx.moveTo(400, 300);
                ctx.lineTo(350 + (i * 10), 400);
                ctx.moveTo(400, 300);
                ctx.lineTo(450 - (i * 10), 400);
                ctx.stroke();
            }

            // Arms details
            for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
                ctx.beginPath();
                ctx.moveTo(400, 150);
                ctx.lineTo(300 - (i * 10), 200);
                ctx.moveTo(400, 150);
                ctx.lineTo(500 + (i * 10), 200);
                ctx.stroke();
            }
        }

        drawSkeleton();
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:

1. **HTML Structure**: The HTML consists of a `<canvas>` element where the skeleton will be drawn.
2. **CSS Styles**: The CSS styles center the canvas in the browser window and set a black background for better visibility of the white lines representing the skeleton.
3. **JavaScript**: The JavaScript code draws the skeleton using the Canvas API. It includes various body parts represented by lines and arcs:
   - Head is represented by a circular arc.
   - Neck and Body are drawn as lines.
   - Arms and Legs are drawn with lines extending from the body.
   - Additional details such as ribs are included using arcs.

You can adjust the positions, lengths, and angles of the lines and arcs to make the skeleton drawing more precise if needed. Enjoy customizing your skeleton!

Certainly! Below is an updated HTML file that draws a human skeleton on a canvas, creates a bitmap of that skeleton, and then tiles the background with miniature versions of it. This is done by first drawing the skeleton on an offscreen canvas, and then using that image as the background image for the body. You can save this code into an HTML file (e.g., `skeleton-tiled.html`) and open it in a web browser.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Tiled Skeleton Background</title>
    <style>
        body {
            margin: 0;
            background-color: black; /* Sets the background color */
            overflow: hidden; /* Hides scrollbars */
        }
        canvas {
            display: block; /* Eliminates spaces around the canvas */
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <canvas id="skeletonCanvas" width="800" height="600"></canvas>
    <script>
        const canvas = document.getElementById('skeletonCanvas');
        const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');

        const bitmapCanvas = document.createElement('canvas');
        const bitmapContext = bitmapCanvas.getContext('2d');
        bitmapCanvas.width = 100; // Width for the smaller skeleton
        bitmapCanvas.height = 100; // Height for the smaller skeleton

        function drawSkeleton(ctx, xOffset = 0, yOffset = 0, scale = 1) {
            ctx.save();
            ctx.translate(xOffset, yOffset);
            ctx.scale(scale, scale);

            ctx.strokeStyle = 'white';
            ctx.lineWidth = 2;

            // Head
            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.arc(400, 70, 30, 0, Math.PI * 2);
            ctx.stroke();

            // Neck
            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.moveTo(400, 100);
            ctx.lineTo(400, 130);
            ctx.stroke();

            // Body
            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.moveTo(400, 130);
            ctx.lineTo(400, 300);
            ctx.stroke();

            // Arms
            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.moveTo(400, 150);
            ctx.lineTo(300, 200);
            ctx.moveTo(400, 150);
            ctx.lineTo(500, 200);
            ctx.stroke();

            // Legs
            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.moveTo(400, 300);
            ctx.lineTo(350, 400);
            ctx.moveTo(400, 300);
            ctx.lineTo(450, 400);
            ctx.stroke();

            // Ribs
            for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
                ctx.beginPath();
                ctx.arc(400, 130 + (i * 13), 30, 0, Math.PI);
                ctx.stroke();
            }

            ctx.restore();
        }

        // Draw the skeleton on the bitmap canvas
        drawSkeleton(bitmapContext, 0, 0, 0.25); // Draw a smaller skeleton

        // Create a pattern from the bitmap canvas and set it as the background
        const pattern = ctx.createPattern(bitmapCanvas, 'repeat');

        // Fill the main canvas with the tiled pattern
        ctx.fillStyle = pattern;
        ctx.fillRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);

        // Draw the main skeleton on the canvas
        drawSkeleton(ctx, 400, 300); // Draw the full-size skeleton
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:

1. **Tiling the Background**: An offscreen canvas (`bitmapCanvas`) is created to draw a smaller version of the skeleton. This smaller version is then used to create a repeating pattern using `createPattern`.
2. **Main Canvas**: The main canvas is filled with the tiled pattern before drawing the full-sized skeleton.
3. **Drawing Function**: The `drawSkeleton` function is now capable of drawing the skeleton at different scales and offsets, allowing for both the small and large versions.
4. **Body Styles**: The `body` style includes `overflow: hidden` to prevent scrollbars since we are filling the entire screen with a background.

You can adjust the scaling factor in the `drawSkeleton(bitmapContext, 0, 0, 0.25);` line to increase or decrease the size of the tiled skeletons. Enjoy your tiled skeleton background!

To create a tile map that stores miniature versions of the skeleton and uses that as a background in a tiled manner, the following HTML code can be utilized. In this example, we will create a small tile map and then use it to fill the background of the main canvas.

Here's the complete code:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Miniature Skeleton Tilemap</title>
    <style>
        body {
            margin: 0;
            background-color: black; /* Background color for body */
            overflow: hidden; /* Hides scrollbars */
        }
        canvas {
            display: block; /* Eliminates spaces around the canvas */
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <canvas id="skeletonCanvas" width="800" height="600"></canvas>
    <script>
        const mainCanvas = document.getElementById('skeletonCanvas');
        const mainCtx = mainCanvas.getContext('2d');

        // Create a small canvas for the tilemap
        const tileCanvas = document.createElement('canvas');
        const tileContext = tileCanvas.getContext('2d');
        const tileSize = 100; // Size of each tile in the tilemap
        tileCanvas.width = tileSize;
        tileCanvas.height = tileSize;

        function drawSkeleton(ctx, xOffset = 0, yOffset = 0, scale = 1) {
            ctx.save();
            ctx.translate(xOffset, yOffset);
            ctx.scale(scale, scale);

            ctx.strokeStyle = 'white';
            ctx.lineWidth = 2;

            // Head
            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.arc(400, 70, 30, 0, Math.PI * 2);
            ctx.stroke();

            // Neck
            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.moveTo(400, 100);
            ctx.lineTo(400, 130);
            ctx.stroke();

            // Body
            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.moveTo(400, 130);
            ctx.lineTo(400, 300);
            ctx.stroke();

            // Arms
            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.moveTo(400, 150);
            ctx.lineTo(300, 200);
            ctx.moveTo(400, 150);
            ctx.lineTo(500, 200);
            ctx.stroke();

            // Legs
            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.moveTo(400, 300);
            ctx.lineTo(350, 400);
            ctx.moveTo(400, 300);
            ctx.lineTo(450, 400);
            ctx.stroke();

            // Ribs
            for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
                ctx.beginPath();
                ctx.arc(400, 130 + (i * 13), 30, 0, Math.PI);
                ctx.stroke();
            }

            ctx.restore();
        }

        // Draw the miniature skeleton on the tile canvas
        drawSkeleton(tileContext, 0, 0, 0.25); // Draw a smaller skeleton for the tile

        // Create a pattern from the tile canvas and set it as the background
        const pattern = mainCtx.createPattern(tileCanvas, 'repeat');

        // Fill the main canvas with the tiled pattern
        mainCtx.fillStyle = pattern;
        mainCtx.fillRect(0, 0, mainCanvas.width, mainCanvas.height);

        // Draw the main (full-size) skeleton on the main canvas
        drawSkeleton(mainCtx, 400, 300); // Draw at center
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:

1. **Tile Canvas**: The `tileCanvas` is created as an offscreen canvas where a miniature version of the skeleton is drawn. The size of each tile is set to `100x100` pixels.
2. **Draw Skeleton Function**: The `drawSkeleton` function takes scaling into account, allowing for the skeleton to be drawn at different sizes.
3. **Tile Creation**: The skeleton is drawn on the `tileCanvas` at a scaled size of `0.25`, creating a smaller version of the skeletal drawing.
4. **Pattern Creation**: A repeating pattern is created using `createPattern`, which uses the `tileCanvas` as the source. This pattern is then filled into the main canvas.
5. **Main Skeleton**: Finally, the full-size skeleton is drawn at the center of the main canvas.

To see this in effect, save the code into an HTML file (e.g., `miniature-skeleton-tilemap.html`) and open it in a web browser. You will see a full-sized skeleton in the center, surrounded by a tiled background of miniature versions of the skeleton.
